          "body": "Esau's generosity extends to the offer of an escort (33:12) and a garrison of men (33:15). Jacob deflects both with characteristic courtesy and uncharacteristic care for the vulnerable — the children are frail, the nursing flocks cannot be driven hard without dying (33:13). The pace of his journey must be set by the weakest member of the caravan, not by a general's march. This is not mere stalling, though what follows suggests it may also be that. Jacob tells Esau he will eventually come to him at Seir (33:14). Esau departs satisfied, returning to his own territory (33:16). The reconciliation is complete; the brothers are at peace. But the narrator makes no effort to disguise what happens next: Jacob goes to Succoth (33:17), then to Shechem (33:18), and no journey to Seir appears anywhere in the remaining chapters of Genesis. Whether Jacob's promise was a polite deflection from the start or a genuine intention that evaporated once the danger passed, the narrative leaves the tension without resolution. The text's honesty about Jacob's character — even here, after Peniel, after the embrace, after the altar — is one of its most striking features. Grace does not instantly produce perfect integrity."
