          "body": "The chapter's final verse is its theological apex. Jacob erects an altar and calls it El-Elohe-Israel: 'God, the God of Israel' (33:20). The name carries two truths simultaneously. The first is personal: Israel is Jacob's new name, given at Peniel (32:28). The altar name announces that the God of the patriarchs — El, the God of his fathers — is now and specifically Jacob's own God. This is the confession Abraham's life demonstrated, the confession Isaac's life received, and now the confession Jacob's life has earned through twenty years of divine discipline and a night of divine wrestling. The second truth is canonical: the name El-Elohe-Israel will reappear. This altar at Shechem anticipates the later history of Israel — Joshua will renew the covenant at Shechem (Joshua 24:1), and the site will remain a sacred center for the twelve tribes. Jacob's altar names not just a man's God but a nation's God. Every act of altar-building in the patriarchal narrative marks a moment when a human being stops and says: this happened, and God did it, and I will not pass through this place without naming Him. Jacob has come through the most dangerous week of his adult life — the confrontation with Laban, the wrestling at Peniel, the reunion with Esau — and the chapter does not end with his relief. It ends with his worship."
