        "body": "The reconciliation secure, Esau offers to travel together (33:12) or to leave an armed escort (33:15). Both offers are generous — the first assumes a restored brotherhood that travels side by side; the second assumes Jacob might need protection on the road. Jacob declines both, and his reasons are both genuinely pastoral and possibly evasive. The children are frail; the nursing flocks cannot be pushed; one hard day of travel would kill them (33:13). The argument is agrarian and realistic — any shepherd would recognize the logic.\n\nBut the pastoral argument enables a diplomatic separation. Jacob promises Esau he will eventually come to him at Seir (33:14) and asks only to 'find favor in the sight of my lord' — the same phrase he used for the gifts (33:8). The promise to come to Seir is stated as a genuine intention: 'until I come to my lord at Seir.' Esau accepts it and returns to his territory (33:16). The narrator, however, does not let it rest there. Jacob immediately goes to Succoth (33:17), then to Shechem (33:18), and nowhere in the subsequent Genesis narrative does he travel to Seir. The gap between 33:14 and 33:17 is one of the Old Testament's quiet indictments of Jacob's character.\n\nScholars divide on whether the promise to Esau was sincere or strategic. Gordon Wenham (Word Biblical Commentary on Genesis) reads it as genuine but unfulfilled — Jacob's plan changed as circumstances changed. Victor Hamilton (NICOT) notes that the narrator seems to flag the discrepancy deliberately: 'Jacob journeyed to Succoth' (33:17) comes immediately after 'until I come to my lord at Seir' (33:14), creating an implicit contradiction. The more uncomfortable reading is that the old Jacob — the heel-grasper who managed every situation — is still present even in the hour of reconciliation. Peniel changed Jacob's name and gave him a limp; it did not instantly produce perfect integrity.\n\nThe theological value of this observation is substantial. The narrator's refusal to sanitize Jacob is one of the Hebrew Bible's most consistent features. Abraham lied twice about Sarah (12:11-13; 20:2); Isaac repeated the same lie (26:7); Jacob deceives his father, manages his brother, and apparently deflects his promise to come to Seir. The patriarchal narratives are not hero-legends; they are honest accounts of how the God of Israel works through flawed, sometimes duplicitous, covenant partners. God's faithfulness to the covenant does not depend on the covenant partner's consistent truthfulness. That is grace of a different order than Esau's embrace, but it is grace nonetheless."
