        "body": "The word shalem in verse 18 — 'Jacob came safely' — is the narrative's formal signal that a vow has been completed. At Bethel, before he fled to Paddan-aram, Jacob had made a conditional vow: 'if God will be with me and will keep me on this journey that I take... so that I return to my father's house in safety (shalom), then the LORD will be my God' (28:20-21). The narrator now echoes the vocabulary: Jacob came shalem — in wholeness, in peace, in the condition his vow named — to the land of Canaan. God kept His end. Jacob is back.\n\nThe specification 'which is in the land of Canaan' (33:18) is more than geographical precision. It is covenantal notation. Every significant patriarchal moment in Canaan is marked by the land-designation because the land is the promise. Shechem is particularly loaded: it is where Abraham entered Canaan and heard God say 'to your descendants I will give this land,' after which Abraham built an altar (12:6-7). Jacob arrives at Abraham's first Canaanite altar-site. The promise that began with Abraham's entrance is being taken up again by Abraham's grandson. The patriarchal narrative has a deliberate geographical structure — promises are made at named places, and narrative fulfillments happen at the same named places.\n\nThe land purchase from the sons of Hamor (33:19) is a faith-act in the tradition of Abraham's purchase of Machpelah (Genesis 23). Abraham bought a burial cave in the promised land before he possessed any of it, as a down-payment on the promise. Jacob buys a field in Shechem before the nation Israel possesses any of the land, as another down-payment. The purchase uses qesitah — a unit of measure used only three times in the Hebrew Bible (here; Joshua 24:32; Job 42:11), suggesting an archaic currency or weight, the exact nature of which is uncertain. The precision of the purchase price underscores the legal reality of the transaction: Jacob does not squat on the land; he buys it, establishing a documented claim in Canaan soil.\n\nThe later note in Joshua 24:32 reveals the full significance: Joseph's bones, brought out of Egypt at the exodus (Exodus 13:19), are eventually buried in this very field Jacob bought (Joshua 24:32). The plot of ground at Shechem becomes the patriarchal inheritance connecting Jacob's arrival to the final resolution of the exodus. Jacob buys the ground; four hundred years later, Joseph's bones come home to it. The faith-act of 33:19 has a four-century horizon."
