        "number": 5,
        "title": "El-Elohe-Israel — the altar that names the God and the man",
        "range": "33:20",
        "excerpt": "Then he erected there an altar and called it El-Elohe-Israel.",
        "body": "The chapter's final verse is its theological destination. Jacob erects an altar at Shechem and names it El-Elohe-Israel: 'God, the God of Israel.' Every word of the name carries weight. El is the ancient Semitic name for God — the powerful one, the transcendent deity. Elohim is the plural of majesty, used throughout Genesis for the creator God. Israel is Jacob's new name, received at Peniel on the night he wrestled with God (32:28). The altar name therefore makes a claim in three movements: the one true God (El) is the God of covenant (Elohim) and He is specifically, personally, historically the God of this man whose name He changed.\n\nThe pattern of altar-building in the patriarchal narrative is consistent and deliberate. Abraham built altars at Shechem (12:7), Bethel (12:8), Hebron (13:18), and Moriah (22:9). Isaac built an altar at Beersheba (26:25). Each altar marks a moment of encounter, promise, or deliverance — the patriarch stops and raises a stone so that the place becomes a testimony. Jacob's altar at Shechem follows the pattern exactly. It is raised at the end of his long journey home, at the site where the Abrahamic covenant was first announced in Canaan, and it names the God who kept him through twenty years, a wrestling match, a feared reunion, and a day of grace that overturned everything he feared.\n\nThe name El-Elohe-Israel is the chapter's answer to Jacob's fear. He had feared Esau's face (32:7); he saw in Esau's face the face of God (33:10). He had feared the journey back to Canaan; he arrived shalem (33:18). He had made a vow at Bethel (28:20-21); it is now complete. The altar does not celebrate Jacob's management of the situation — his gifts, his prostrations, his careful family arrangements. It celebrates the God who worked through all of it, including through Esau's inexplicable grace, to bring a limping, renamed, covenant-keeping God's man home. Swindoll observes that this is the pattern of the entire Jacob narrative: God is the Hound of Heaven who pursues, disciplines, wounds, and finally brings home the man He has chosen — not because of what the man deserves, but because of what the covenant requires.\n\nThe significance of the altar's location at Shechem extends beyond Jacob's lifetime. Joshua will renew the covenant at Shechem after the conquest (Joshua 24:1-28), gathering all Israel there and calling them to choose whom they will serve. The altar Jacob builds becomes a prototype for covenant renewal at the same site. When Joshua stands at Shechem to call Israel to covenant faithfulness, he is standing where their ancestor Jacob first named God as El-Elohe-Israel — the God who brought him home. The final verse of Genesis 33 is not a personal postscript; it is the planting of a seed that will flower in the national life of Israel for generations.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mizbeach* (altar, v.20) from the root *zabach* — to slaughter, to sacrifice. The altar is not merely a monument; it is a place of offering. *El-Elohe-Israel* — the name is formally equivalent to 'God, [who is] the God of Israel.' Compare Exodus 3:6: 'I am the God of your father, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, the God of Jacob' — the pattern of personal divine self-identification that this altar name anticipates."
